photo.title: Georg Schermer, d. 1597
photo.description: In Georgio Schermero p[re]ceptori suo obseruandiss. [dono dedit?] [Possibly Georg Schermer (d. 1597). Per VIAF, he was a theologian, educator and pastor, with appointments at the Universität Greifswald as a professor of theology and at a school at Stargard in Pommern (now Stargard Szczeciński, Poland) as rector. In Isaac Lelong's Hondertjaarige jubelgedachtenisse der akademie van Utrecht (Amsterdam: Vieroot, 1736), p. 196, "Georgius Schermerus" is stated to have founded the school at Stargard in 1549; the Hausbuch des Herrn Joachim von Wedel, ed. Julius Freiherr von Bohlen Bohlendorff (Tübingen, 1882), p. 210, confirms that he is "rector scholae" there in 1565. Again per VIAF, he also appears to have held a pastorate in Stargard.] DNB heading: Schermer, Georg ‡d -1597 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 K7498 552a All images from this book Penn Libraries catalog record

photo.description: Woodcut llustration of a well-dressed humanoid figure with the eyes of a lynx, the ears of a pig, the neck of a swan or snake, and the right foot of a bear. A lion's head is on its breast; from its mouth protrude a sword and a spray of lily leaves. The figure holds a closed purse in its right hand and is dropping coins from its left. photo.title: Woodcut illustration of Grammar as a memory image from Johann Horst von Romberch's work on memory, Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533)
photo.description: Woodcut illustration of Grammar as a memory image from Johann Horst von Romberch's work on memory, Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533). "This is one of the very rare cases in which memory image is illustrated; and the image turns out to be the familiar figure of old Grammatica, the first of the liberal arts, with some of her familiar attributes, the scalpel and the ladder. She is here not only the well-known personification of the liberal art of Grammar, but a memory image being used to remember material about grammar through inscriptions on her. The inscription across her chest and the images near or on her are derived from Romberch's visual alphabets, both the 'objects' ones and the 'birds' one which he is using in combination."--F.A. Yates, The Art of Memory (London: Pimlico, 1992), p. 126. Established heading: Sessa, Melchiorre, ‡d fl. 1506-1549 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H7958 520c 1533 All images from this book

photo.description: Woodcut diagram of a portion of a visual alphabet and its application from Johann Horst von Romberch's work on memory, Congestorium artificiose memorie (Venice: Melchiorre Sessa, 1533). "Visual alphabets are ways of representing letters of the alphabet by images. These are formed in various ways; for example with pictures of objects whose shape resemble [sic] letters of the alphabet, as compasses or a ladder for A; or a hoe for N. Another way is through pictures of animals or birds arranged in the order of the first letter of their names, as A for Anser, goose, B for Bubo, owl."--F.A. Yates, The Art of Memory (London: Pimlico, 1992), p. 124-125. Established heading: Sessa, Melchiorre, ‡d fl. 1506-1549 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H7958 520c 1533 All images from this book

The poem's dedicatee, Paul III's grandson Alessandro Cardinal Farnese, was a power broker in the conclave which elected Julius III as a compromise candidate. photo.description: Anno d[omi]nj mil[lesim]o cccco s[e]xig[esim]o [sic?] nono declaratum est in consilio basiliensi beatissim{am?} vi[r]gine[m?] nu[m]q[uam] subiacuisse peccato originali quod semper [...] verum[?] l[...] [...] [...] co[n]silij determinatione[m?] plures aliter [...] [...] processu semp[...] quod[?] se[m]per suis [...] [...] resolutione co[n]clusum est spiritu[?] [...] [...] [The first hand is probably recording the approbation of the Doctrine of the Immaculate Conception by the Council of Basel on 18 December 1439. ("AD 1469" in line one is probably an error for "1439" because the Council of Basel ran from 1431-1445.) This approbation never "took" in the church at large because the Council's authoritative status was undermined by its subsequent deposition of Pope Eugene IV and appointment of the anti-pope Felix V. The doctrine wasn't formally promulgated as dogma until 1854, though the Council of Basel's statement on the matter was often used to support it.] Penn Libraries call number: IC5 T5988 524l All images from this book

photo.title: Woodcut coat of arms of the House of Wittelsbach
photo.description: Woodcut coat of arms of the House of Wittelsbach (the arms of Palatinate quartered with those of Bavaria (Wittelsbach)): The Golden Lion represents the administrative region of Upper Palatinate. The inescutcheon of white and blue fusils askance was originally the coat of arms of the Counts of Bogen, adopted in 1247 by the House of Wittelsbach. The white-and-blue fusils are indisputably the emblem of Bavaria and these arms today symbolize Bavaria as a whole. The dedication reads: "Illustrissimo principi, ac Domino, Domino Alberto, Comiti Palatino Rheni, superioris, inferioris que Bavariae Duci. Domino suo clementissimo. Osvaldus ab Eck S.D." At the time this book was published (1541), there were two concurrent Dukes of Bavaria, older brother William (i.e. Wilhelm) IV of Bavaria (1493-1550), Duke of Bavaria from 1508 to 1550, and until 1545 together with his younger brother Louis (i.e. Ludwig) X, Duke of Bavaria. Both sons of Albert IV, Duke of Bavaria. All of these were members of the House of Wittelsbach, and presumably the double helm & crest indicate the concurrent Dukes. photo.title: Inscription to George Glass Kennaway (ca. 1824-1868?)
photo.description: George G. Kennaway - From His Mother. April 1855. Probably George Glass Kennaway (ca. 1824-1868?) of Hoopern House, Exeter, Devon, UK, son of the Exeter solicitor and liberal politician Mark Kennaway and his wife Harriet (née Codrington). George matriculated at Christ Church College, Oxford, in 1842 at age 18 and took his BA in 1846 and his MA in 1848; cf. J. Foster, Alumni Oxonienses (Oxford: Parker & Co., 1888), v. 2, p. 786. He contributed to the restoration of Wynard's Chapel (also called Trinity Chapel, but not to be confused with the nearby Holy Trinity Church) in Exeter, where he is buried. According to B. Cresswell, Exeter Churches (Exeter: J.G. Commin, 1908) p. 61, his epitaph reads: Here lieth George Glass Kennaway, of Christchurch, Oxon. Eldest son of Mark Kennaway of Hoopern Esqr., by Harriet Codrington second daughter of George Daniel of this city. A cheerful restorer of this ancient chapel and Gods House, a liberal benefactor to the pries [sic] and the poor. He deceased Dec. xxxi mdccclxvii in the xlvi year of his age. For "mdccclxvii" read "1868," I think, judging from the fact that his death at age 45 (the 46th year of his age) was registered in early 1869; cf. information transcribed by FreeBMD from the civil registration index of births, marriages and deaths for England and Wales. Harvard Library MS Eng 898 ("Sonnets, and Poems, written by John Bampfylde Esqr.") evidently has Kennaways ownership inscription, dated 1863 at Hoopern House. Cf. C.R. Woodring, "Charles Lamb in the Harvard Library" in Harvard Library Bulletin 10.2 (1956), p. 210, n. 5. For his mother, Harriet Codrington Kennaway (d. 1861), see her obituary notice in The London Review 3 (1861), p. 332. Penn Libraries call number: EC8 T3257 853e All images from this book

photo.title: Harrow School prize certificate awarded to Harry Amyas Leigh Herschel Wade (1873-1959) by Edward E. Bowen in 1888
photo.description: Harry Amyas Leigh Herschel Wade (1873-1959), fourth son of Sir Thomas Francis Wade (1818-1895), the diplomat and Sinologist ("Wade" of the Wade-Giles system of romanization), and his wife Amelia Herschel (1841-1926), daughter of the astronomer John Herschel. Harry was born in Peking (now Beijing); Sir Thomas retired to England in 1888, the same year Harry entered Harrow (along with classmate Winston Churchill!). Harry left Harrow in 1890 and joined the army in 1893, rising to the rank of major by 1910, and was decorated for his service during the Nile Expedition and the Boer War (his eldest brother Alexander was killed in action in the latter conflict). Harry also served in the Great War (on the staff of the 1st Army Corps in France and then as military attaché in Denmark) and was brevetted Lieutenant-Colonel in 1918. In that same year he led a three-member diplomatic mission to Poland and subsequently accompanied Ignacy Paderewski on his return to that country in 1919. Harry Wade appears to have had some talent as a writer and editor, publishing articles on military subjects and editing the Army Review in 1912 and the League of Nations Union in 1919. After leaving the army in 1921, he was an official of the League of Nations and then of the World Court until his retirement in 1937. His obituary in the Times of London notes that he was one of the League's chief "spontaneous translators" [i.e. interpreters]. He was appointed research officer of the United Nations War Crimes Commission in 1944, took part in the Nuremberg trials, and wrote chapters 6 and 7, as well as some of the appendices, of History of the United Nations War Crimes Commission and the Development of the Laws of War (London: HMSO, 1948). He died in 1959. Edward Ernest Bowen (1859-1901) taught at Harrow from 1859 until his death in 1901 and wrote the school song, "Forty Years On." photo.title: Woodcut device of Strasbourg printer Mathias Apiarius, ca. 1500-1554
photo.description: The printer’s device of Mathias Apiarius (ca. 1500-1554) features a bear discovering a bee's nest in the hollow of a tree. At the base of the tree there is a Bible and bees are flying around. The device also features one inscription in Greek and three inscriptions in Latin (Below: "Omnia probate, quod bonum fuerit tenete. 1. Thess. 5.; On the right side: "Quam dulcia faucibus meis eloquia tua, super mel orimeo. Psal. 118. On the left side: "Vrsus insidians & esuriens, princeps impius super populum pauperem. Thre. 3. Prouerb. 28. ) The inscriptions help to explain the meaning of the woodcut: the bear is about to remove a huge mallet hung upon a branch before the hole which contains honey; the mallet will naturally always fall back on him. The device alludes to the name of the printer: Apiarius is the latinized form of the German family name Biener which means "bee master". Established heading: Apiarius, Mathias, approximately 1500-1554 Penn Libraries call number: IC5 R3590 533a 1535 All images from this book
